Cochrane Database of Systematic reviews Review - Intervention

Higher versus lower protein intake in formula‐fed term infants

  • Alejandro G Gonzalez-Garay
  • Aurora E Serralde-Zúñiga
  • Isabel Medina Vera
  • Liliana Velasco Hidalgo
  • Mathy Victoria Alonso Ocaña
Authors' declarations of interest

Version published: 06 November 2023 Version history

https://doi.org/10.1002/14651858.CD013758.pub2
Collapse all Expand all

Abstract

available in
  • English
  • Español
  • فارسی
  • Français
  • 한국어
  • 简体中文

    • Background

    Many infants are fed infant formulas to promote growth. Some formulas have a high protein content (≥ 2.5 g per 100 kcal) to accelerate weight gain during the first year of life. The risk‐benefit balance of these formulas is unclear.

    Objectives

    To evaluate the benefits and harms of higher protein intake versus lower protein intake in healthy, formula‐fed term infants.

    Search methods

    We searched CENTRAL, MEDLINE, Embase, CINAHL, LILACS, OpenGrey, clinical trial registries, and conference proceedings in October 2022.

    Selection criteria

    We included randomized controlled trials (RCTs) of healthy formula‐fed infants (those fed only formula and those given formula as a complementary food). We included infants of any sex or ethnicity who were fed infant formula for at least three consecutive months at any time from birth. We excluded quasi‐randomized trials, observational studies, and infants with congenital malformations or serious underlying diseases. We defined high protein content as 2.5 g or more per 100 kcal, and low protein content as less than 1.8 g per 100 kcal (for exclusive formula feeding) or less than 1.7 g per 100 kcal (for complementary formula feeding).

    Data collection and analysis

    Four review authors independently assessed the risk of bias and extracted data from trials, and a fifth review author resolved discrepancies. We performed random‐effects meta‐analyses, calculating risk ratios (RRs) or Peto odds ratios (Peto ORs) with 95% confidence intervals (CIs) for dichotomous outcomes, and mean differences (MDs) with 95% CIs for continuous outcomes. We used the GRADE approach to evaluate the certainty of the evidence.

    Main results

    We included 11 RCTs (1185 infants) conducted in high‐income countries. Seven trials (1629 infants) compared high‐protein formula against standard‐protein formula, and four trials (256 infants) compared standard‐protein formula against low‐protein formula. The longest follow‐up was 11 years.

    High‐protein formula versus standard‐protein formula

    We found very low‐certainty evidence that feeding healthy term infants high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula has little or no effect on underweight (MD in weight‐for‐age z‐score 0.05 SDs, 95% CI −0.09 to 0.19; P = 0.51, I2 = 61%; 7 studies, 1629 participants), stunting (MD in height‐for‐age z‐score 0.15 SDs, 95% CI −0.05 to 0.35; P = 0.14, I2 = 73%; 7 studies, 1629 participants), and wasting (MD in weight‐for‐height z‐score −0.12 SDs, 95% CI −0.31 to 0.07; P = 0.20, I2 = 94%; 7 studies, 1629 participants) in the first year of life.

    We found very low‐certainty evidence that feeding healthy infants high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula has little or no effect on the occurrence of overweight (RR 1.26, 95% CI 0.63 to 2.51; P = 0.51; 1 study, 1090 participants) or obesity (RR 1.96, 95% CI 0.59 to 6.48; P = 0.27; 1 study, 1090 participants) at five years of follow‐up.

    No studies reported all‐cause mortality.

    Feeding healthy infants high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula may have little or no effect on the occurrence of adverse events such as diarrhea, vomiting, or milk hypersensitivity (RR 0.93, 95% CI 0.76 to 1.13; P = 0.44, I2 = 0%; 4 studies, 445 participants; low‐certainty evidence) in the first year of life.

    Standard‐protein formula versus low‐protein formula

    We found very low‐certainty evidence that feeding healthy infants standard‐protein formula compared to low‐protein formula has little or no effect on underweight (MD in weight‐for‐age z‐score 0.0, 95% CI −0.43 to 0.43; P = 0.99, I2 = 81%; 4 studies, 256 participants), stunting (MD in height‐for‐age z‐score −0.01, 95% CI −0.36 to 0.35; P = 0.96, I2 = 73%; 4 studies, 256 participants), and wasting (MD in weight‐for‐height z‐score 0.13, 95% CI −0.29 to 0.56; P = 0.54, I2 = 95%; 4 studies, 256 participants) in the first year of life.

    No studies reported overweight, obesity, or all‐cause mortality.

    Feeding healthy infants standard‐protein formula compared to low‐protein formula may have little or no effect on the occurrence of adverse events such as diarrhea, vomiting, or milk hypersensitivity (Peto OR 1.55, 95% CI 0.70 to 3.40; P = 0.28, I2 = 0%; 2 studies, 206 participants; low‐certainty evidence) in the first four months of life.

    Authors' conclusions

    We are unsure if feeding healthy infants high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula has an effect on undernutrition, overweight, or obesity. There may be little or no difference in the risk of adverse effects between infants fed with high‐protein formula versus those fed with standard‐protein formula.

    We are unsure if feeding healthy infants standard‐protein formula compared to low‐protein formula has any effect on undernutrition. There may be little or no difference in the risk of adverse effects between infants fed with standard‐protein formula versus those fed with low‐protein formula.

    The findings of six ongoing studies and two studies awaiting classification studies may change the conclusions of this review.

    • Higher‐protein formula versus lower‐protein formula: which works better to prevent malnutrition and obesity in infants?

    Key messages

    1. We are unsure if high‐protein formula affects malnutrition or obesity in infants.
    2. Larger studies are needed to further evaluate the benefits and potential harms of the different types of formula.
    3. Future research should focus on long‐term growth and brain development.

    What are high‐ and low‐protein infant formulas?

    Infant formulas have a similar nutritional content to breast milk, and contain ingredients such as cow's milk, fats, vitamins, proteins (such as whey or soy protein), and carbohydrates. Depending on the amount of protein they contain, formulas are categorized as low‐protein (less than 1.8 g per 100 kcal), standard‐protein, or high‐protein (2.5 g or more per 100 kcal).

    Why is it important to study infant formula?

    Despite World Health Organization (WHO) recommendations, many full‐term infants around the world are fed formula instead of breast milk. Some infant formulas contain more that the recommended amount of protein; they are designed to increase weight gain in infants during the first year of life. However, we do not know the effect of high‐protein formula on malnutrition, overweight, or obesity during infancy.

    What did we want to find out?

    We wanted to find out whether high protein formula is better than standard or low protein formula for preventing:
    1. malnutrition (low weight for age, low height for age, or low weight or height);
    2. overweight or obesity (high weight for height); and
    3. other unwanted events.

    What did we do?

    We searched for studies examining higher‐protein formula compared with lower‐protein formula in healthy infants of either sex, born at nine months of pregnancy and with normal birth weight and height.

    We compared and summarized the results of the studies, and rated our confidence in the evidence based on factors such as study methods and sizes.

    What did we find?

    We found 11 eligible studies involving 1885 healthy, full‐term, formula‐fed infants. Seven studies (1629 infants) compared high‐protein formula with standard‐protein formula, and four studies (256 infants) compared standard‐protein formula with low‐protein formula. The biggest study included 1090 infants, and the smallest study included 20 infants. Ten studies were conducted in Europe and one in the USA. Most studies lasted approximately four months; only two studies lasted five years or more. Pharmaceutical companies funded all the studies.

    Overall, we are unsure if feeding healthy infants high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula has any effect on undernutrition, overweight, or obesity in the first year of life. We are unsure if feeding healthy infants standard‐protein formula compared to low‐protein formula has any effect on undernutrition in childhood. The occurrence of unwanted events in formula‐fed infants may be unrelated to the protein content of the formula.

    What are the limitations of the evidence

    We are not confident about the evidence because the studies provided information in different ways, and the results varied considerably across studies. Moreover, some studies had many dropouts, which could have affected the results. Further research is likely to modify the results of this review.

    How up to date is this evidence?

    The evidence is current to October 2022.

    Visual summary

    Authors' conclusions

    Implications for practice

    High‐protein formula versus standard‐protein formula

    We are unsure if feeding healthy term infants high‐protein formula (> 2.5 g per 100 kcal) compared with standard‐protein formula (1.8 g to < 2.5 g per 100 kcal) has an effect on undernutrition (underweight, stunting, or wasting) in the first year of life, regardless of whether the infants are exclusively formula‐fed or are given formula in addition complementary foods.

    We are unsure if feeding healthy term infants high‐protein formula compared with standard‐protein formula has an effect on the risk of overweight or obesity in the first five years of life.

    Only one study reported neurodevelopmental outcomes, and no studies reported all‐cause mortality.

    The evidence suggests that there is little or no difference in the risk of adverse events between infants fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula, either exclusively or with complementary foods, in the first year of life.

    We are unsure if feeding healthy term infants high‐protein formula compared with standard‐protein formula, either exclusively or with complementary foods, has an effect on anthropometric measurements, such as weight, height, body mass index (BMI), and head circumference in the first year of life. No studies reported arm circumference.

    Standard‐protein formula versus low‐protein formula

    We are unsure if feeding healthy term infants standard‐protein formula, compared with low‐protein formula (< 1.8 g per 100 kcal) has an effect on undernutrition (underweight, stunting, or wasting) in the first year of life, regardless of whether the infants are exclusively formula‐fed or are given formula with complementary foods.

    No studies reported overweight, obesity, neurodevelopment, or all‐cause mortality.

    The evidence suggests that there is little or no difference in the risk of experiencing adverse events between infants who are exclusively fed standard protein formula and those who are exclusively fed low‐protein formula in the first four months of life. No studies reported adverse events in children who were given formula in addition to complementary foods.

    We are unsure if feeding healthy term infants standard‐protein formula compared with low‐protein formula, either exclusively or with complementary foods, has an effect on anthropometric measurements, such as weight, height, BMI, and head circumference in the first year of life. No studies reported arm circumference.

    Implications for research

    The conclusion of our review may change if and when we incorporate the findings of the six ongoing trials and the two trials pending classification in future updates.

    There is a need for standardized research with lower attrition rates to determine whether the protein content of infant formula has any effect on infant morbidity and neurodevelopment in the short and long term. This information is necessary to establish adequate feeding programs for ensuring the optimal growth and development of infants.

    Background

    Description of the condition

    The United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) and the World Health Organization (WHO) clearly support breastfeeding as the ideal form of nutrition for the newborn. This is because breast milk provides the energy and nutrients necessary for safe and proper growth and development. Breastfeeding further offers protection against the development of food allergies, malnutrition, and respiratory and gastrointestinal infections, which are some of the leading causes of death in children aged under five years worldwide (AAP 2012; WHO 2018). Despite these benefits, the prevalence of breastfeeding at 12 months is low: from 1% to 35% in high‐ and upper middle‐income countries, and from 76% to 85% in low‐ and lower middle‐income countries (AAP 2012; Ip 2007; Szucs 2011; Victoria 2016; WHO 2018).

    According to WHO, malnutrition is an imbalance between the intake of energy or nutrients (or both) in a person. It is classified into the following three types.

    1. Undernutrition: a nutritional deficiency resulting from insufficient food intake, or the inability to convert or absorb food, which is often accompanied by repeated infections (UNICEF 2020; WHO 2020). Undernutrition manifests in the following three ways.

      1. Underweight: when the weight of a person is much lower than average for their age (weight for age more than 2 standard deviations (SDs) below the median of the WHO Child Growth Standards; WHO 2010; WHO standards 2023).

      2. Stunting or growth retardation: the result of long‐term nutritional deprivation (height for age more than 2 SDs below the median of the WHO Child Growth Standards; WHO 2010; WHO standards 2023).

      3. Wasting: a consequence of insufficient food intake that increases the risk of infectious diseases and death (weight for height more than 2 SDs below the median of the WHO Child Growth Standards; WHO 2010; WHO standards 2023).

    2. Micronutrient‐related malnutrition: a deficiency of important vitamins and minerals or micronutrient excess (WHO 2010).

    3. Overweight or obesity: excessive fat accumulation that may impair health, classified as follows.

      1. Overweight: weight for height more than 2 SDs above the median of the WHO Child Growth Standards (WHO 2010; WHO standards 2023).

      2. Obesity: weight for height more than 3 SDs above the median of the WHO Child Growth Standards (WHO 2010; WHO standards 2023).

    Description of the intervention

    Infants who are not exclusively breastfed can receive breast milk substitutes (Victoria 2016). These substitutes are formulas made from cow's milk, serum proteins, vegetable oils, and carbohydrates; their physical characteristics and nutritional and energy composition resemble those of human milk. The aim of formula feeding is to promote the normal growth and development of infants (Koletzko 2005; Vermilyea 2015).

    Different types of infant formulas are available to address to the varying nutritional needs of newborns. For example, formulas for preterm infants can have additional thickeners and modified carbohydrates, fats, or proteins. Infant formulas for healthy infants (i.e. infants with a weight and height at birth between the 10th and 90th percentiles for age) are constituted according to the recommendations of the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) Codex Alimentarius Commission (Butte 2005; Codex 2017), and the European Society for Paediatric Gastroenterology Hepatology and Nutrition (ESPGHAN; Dalmau Serra 2015; Koletzko 2005; Koletzko 2012).

    Infant formula, when used as the sole source of food in infants during the first six months of life, should provide 60 kilocalories (kcal) to 70 kcal of energy per 100 mL, and have the following composition.

    1. Carbohydrates (9 g to 14 g per 100 kcal)

    2. Fats (4.4 g to 6 g per 100 kcal)

    3. Proteins (1.8 g to 2.5 g per 100 kcal of cow's milk whey protein, or 2.25 g to 3 g per 100 kcal of soy protein isolate)

    4. Vitamins, minerals, trace elements, and other micronutrients

    From six months of age, infants can receive follow‐up formula in addition to complementary foods. It should have broadly the same nutrient content as formula given to younger infants, but provide slightly less protein (1.7 g to 2.5 g per 100 kcal of cow's milk whey proteins, or 2.1 g to 2.5 g per 100 kcal of soy protein isolate).

    The rationale for including a minimum of 1.7 g of protein per 100 kcal of infant formula is to provide essential amino acids to promote brain maturation and mineral absorption in the kidneys, without increasing the development of fatty tissue or decreasing glomerular filtration (Abrams 2015; EFSA 2017; Michaelsen 2012; Oropeza 2018). Despite the FAO and ESPGHAN recommended ranges of 1.8 g to 3 g of protein per 100 kcal, some manufacturers have modified the composition of infant formula to include up to 4.5 g of protein per 100 kcal. This amount of protein is the equivalent of more than 15% additional energy from protein and is intended to accelerate growth during the first year of life for newborns with low birth weight (i.e. below 2500 g). However, this increase in protein may contribute to the development of adverse events such as gastrointestinal intolerance, obesity, metabolic syndrome, and non‐communicable diseases during childhood (Dewey 1993; Haschke 2016; Lind 2017; Madsen 2011; WHO 2016).

    How the intervention might work

    Lower intake of protein decreases the efficiency of its use for tissue accretion and other metabolic functions, leading to deterioration in growth, immune response, nutrition, and neurodevelopment (Koletzko 2009a; WHO 2002). However, consumption of high amounts of protein can have adverse effects. A rapid increase in weight during the first two years of life might be associated with increased risk of obesity in later years (Monteiro 2005; Ong 2006). The hypothesis underpinning high‐protein formulas is that a high energy intake increases plasma concentrations of branched‐chain amino acids such as leucine, which favors insulin secretion and insulin‐like growth factor 1 (IGF‐1). This concentration promotes the activity of a highly conserved protein kinase known as TOR (target of rapamycin), which is a central controller of nutrient‐sensitive cell growth. When activated, it promotes muscle and adipose tissue growth, leading to weight gain and increasing the risk of obesity during childhood (Abrams 2015; Åkeson 1998; Brands 2014; Druet 2012; Fenton 2020; Koletzko 2016; Lind 2017; Lovell 2021; Madsen 2011; Melnik 2015; Michaelsen 2012; Monasta 2010; Monteiro 2005; Scaglioni 2000; Tang 2018; Yang 2013; Zheng 2017).

    Why it is important to do this review

    A large proportion of term infants are fed formula (AIHW 2011; Appleton 2018; CDC 2014; Gutiérrez 2012; Ip 2007; WHO 2018). The protein content of some formulas is higher than recommended by the FAO Codex Alimentarius Commission and the ESPGHAN. According to the manufacturers, the aim of increasing the protein content is to accelerate the growth rate of infants by up to 2.36 g/kg/day. However, some studies have reported that an accelerated growth rate promotes increased adipose tissue as well as increased muscle mass. Increased adipose tissue is associated with overweight or obesity during childhood.

    Given the wide range of available protein contents for formula, it is unclear which is most effective for promoting an appropriate growth rate in term infants without increasing the risk of obesity, overweight, or adverse events. We aimed to address this question in our review.

    Objectives

    To evaluate the benefits and harms of higher protein intake versus lower protein intake in healthy, formula‐fed term infants.

    Methods

    Criteria for considering studies for this review

    Types of studies

    We included randomized controlled trials (RCTs) and cluster‐RCTs of infants who were fed infant formula for at least three consecutive months at any time from birth to two years of age, either exclusively or in addition to complementary foods (WHO 2002).

    We excluded quasi‐randomized trials and observational studies*.

    *See Included studies (Study design) and Differences between protocol and review.

    Types of participants

    We included infants of any sex and ethnicity, born at full term (37 to 42 weeks of gestation), whose weight and length were within 2 SDs of the age‐specific median of the WHO Child Growth Standards (WHO standards 2023). We excluded studies with the following populations.

    1. Infants with congenital malformations (central nervous system, cardiovascular, respiratory, digestive, or musculoskeletal abnormalities)

    2. Infants with other serious underlying illness, including sepsis, cystic fibrosis, untreated congenital hypothyroidism, bronchopulmonary dysplasia, hepatic or renal insufficiency, renal tubular acidosis, and any inborn metabolic errors

    3. Infants with milk hypersensitivity, lactose intolerance, malabsorption syndromes, chronic diarrhea, parenteral nutrition, or fasting periods

    4. Infants fed with soy formula, rice formula, or modified formulas (e.g. anti‐reflux formula, lactose‐free formula, partially or fully hydrolyzed formula)

    Types of interventions

    We evaluated high‐protein formula (≥ 2.5 g per 100 kcal) versus standard‐protein or low‐protein formula. When infant formula was the sole method of feeding, we defined standard protein content as 1.8 g to less than 2.5 g per 100 kcal and low protein content as less than 1.8 g per 100 kcal (Koletzko 2005). When infant formula was given with complementary foods, we defined standard protein intake as 1.7 g to less than 2.5 g per 100 kcal and low protein intake as less than 1.7 g per 100 kcal (Dalmau Serra 2015; Koletzko 2012; Suthutvoravut 2015).

    Types of outcome measures

    Primary outcomes

    1. Undernutrition

      1. Underweight: weight‐for‐age z‐score more than 2 SDs below the median of the WHO Child Growth Standards (WHO standards 2023)

      2. Stunting: height‐for‐age z‐score more than 2 SDs below the median of the WHO Child Growth Standards (WHO standards 2023)

      3. Wasting: weight‐for‐height z‐score more than 2 SDs below the median of the WHO Child Growth Standards (WHO standards 2023)

    2. Overweight or obesity

      1. Overweight: weight‐for‐height z‐score more than 2 SDs above the median of the WHO Child Growth Standards (WHO standards 2023)

      2. Obesity: weight‐for‐height z‐score more than 3 SDs above the median of the WHO Child Growth Standards (WHO standards 2023)

    Timing of outcome measurement (primary outcomes)

    1. In infants who were exclusively formula‐fed: from birth to four months

    2. In infants who were given formula in addition to complementary foods: from six months to five years

    Secondary outcomes

    1. Neurodevelopmental outcomes (e.g. cerebral palsy, mental developmental delays, blindness, deafness, lacking verbal fluency) evaluated by a validated instrument, such as the Bayley scale (Bayley 1993; Bayley 2005)

    2. All‐cause mortality

    3. Adverse events, based on inquiries to the parents and daily records. Possible adverse events include the following.

      1. Diarrhea (three or more loose or liquid stools per day, or more frequently for the individual; WHO diarrhoea 2020)

      2. Vomiting

      3. Abdominal pain (Ortega Páeza 2013)

      4. Constipation (difficulty in defecation for two or more weeks; Baker 1999)

      5. Milk hypersensitivity (atopic dermatitis, skin rash, respiratory symptoms, or diarrhea after 12 to 24 hours of milk ingestion; Goldman 1963; Vandenplas 2007)

      6. Renal insufficiency (glomerular filtration rate < 40 mL/minute/1.73 m2;Chan 2002)

      7. Hyperglycemia (plasma glucose > 150 mg/dL; Hemachandra 1999; Şimşek 2018)

    4. Anthropometric measurements

      1. Weight (kg)

      2. Height (cm)

      3. Body mass index (BMI; kg/m2)

      4. Head circumference (cm)

      5. Arm circumference (cm)

    Timing of outcome measurement (secondary outcomes)

    1. For neurodevelopmental outcomes, all‐cause mortality, and adverse events: at any time after randomization

    2. For anthropometric measurements: from birth to five years

    Search methods for identification of studies

    Cochrane Neonatal's Information Specialist, Michelle Fiander, developed the search strategies in consultation with the review authors.

    Electronic searches

    We searched the following databases in October 2022 without restrictions on language or publication type. We did not restrict trial searches by publication date, but we did restrict the search for systematic reviews to those published from 2020. We used methodological filters to limit retrieval to trials and systematic reviews. Appendix 1 shows the search strategies and methodological filters.

    We searched the following electronic databases.

    1. Cochrane via CRS (Issue 10, 2022; searched 27 October 2022)

    2. Ovid MEDLINE(R) and Epub Ahead of Print, In‐Process, In‐Data‐Review & Other Non‐Indexed Citations, Daily and Versions (1946 to 26 October 2022)

    3. Ovid Embase (1974 to 26 October 2022)

    4. CINAHL Complete (EBSCOhost; 1981 to 27 October 2022)

    5. LILACS (via Virtual Health Library, 27 October 2022)

    We searched the following clinical trial registries for ongoing or recently completed trials.

    1. WHO International Clinical Trials Registry Platform (ICTRP; trialsearch.who.int; searched 27 October 2022)

    2. US National Institutes of Health Ongoing Trials Registry ClinicalTrials.gov (clinicaltrials.gov; searched 27 October 2022)

    3. ISRCTN Registry (www.isrctn.com; searched 28 October 2022)

    Searching other resources

    We attempted to identify other potentially eligible trials or ancillary publications by searching the reference lists of included trials and relevant systematic reviews, meta‐analyses, and clinical practice guidelines.

    We also searched the following sources for conference proceedings and symposiums of the annual meetings up to 27 October 2022.

    1. American Academy of Pediatrics

    2. European Society for Paediatric Research

    3. Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health

    4. Pediatric Academic Societies

    For gray literature, we searched OpenGrey (www.opengrey.eu).

    Data collection and analysis

    We performed the review following the recommendations in the Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews of Interventions and the standard methods of Cochrane Neonatal (Higgins 2022).

    Selection of studies

    We used Cochrane's Screen4Me workflow to help assess the search results. Screen4Me comprises the following three components.

    1. Known assessments: a service that matches records in the search results to records that have already been screened in Cochrane Crowd and been labeled 'RCT' or 'Not an RCT'

    2. RCT classifier: a machine learning model that distinguishes RCTs from non‐RCTs

    3. Cochrane Crowd: Cochrane's citizen science platform where the Crowd help to identify and describe health evidence.

    For more information, see Screen4Me. Previous publications provide detailed information regarding evaluations of the Screen4Me components (Marshall 2018; Noel‐Storr 2021; Thomas 2020).

    Two of four review authors (IM, AS, LV, MA) independently assessed the abstract or title, or both, of each record and eliminated those that were clearly irrelevant. We then retrieved and investigated the full‐text reports of all potentially relevant records. We resolved any discrepancies through discussion or by involving a fifth review author (AG). We included full‐text reports or abstracts of published and unpublished RCTs. We also included observational studies that reported follow‐up of participants included in the original RCTs. We presented an adapted PRISMA flow diagram showing the process of study selection (Liberati 2009).

    Data extraction and management

    Two of four review authors (IM, AS, LV, MA) independently extracted data from the included studies using a standardized data extraction form. For each included trial, we collected information regarding design, methods, participants, interventions, outcomes, and treatment effects. We discussed any disagreement between the review authors with a fifth review author (AG) to achieve a final consensus.

    One review author (AG) entered the data into Cochrane's statistical software Review Manager Web (RevMan Web 2022), and a second review author (MA) checked the entries for accuracy. We attempted to contact the authors of the original reports for further information whenever necessary.

    Assessment of risk of bias in included studies

    Two of four review authors (IM, AS, LV, MA) independently assessed all included trials using the original Cochrane risk of bias tool (RoB 1), assigning a judgment of low, high, or unclear risk of bias for each of the following domains (Higgins 2017).

    1. Sequence generation (selection bias)

    2. Allocation concealment (selection bias)

    3. Blinding of participants and personnel (performance bias)

    4. Blinding of outcome assessment (detection bias)

    5. Incomplete outcome data (attrition bias)

    6. Selective reporting (reporting bias)

    7. Any other bias

    We resolved any disagreements by discussion or by consulting a fifth review author (AG). See Appendix 2 for a more detailed description of the RoB 1 domains.

    Measures of treatment effect

    When at least two studies reported the same outcome within the same comparison, we pooled their results in a meta‐analysis. We expressed dichotomous data as risk ratios (RRs) or Peto odd ratios (Peto ORs) with 95% confidence intervals (CIs). We planned to report the number needed to treat for an additional beneficial outcome (NNTB) or the number needed to treat for an additional harmful outcome (NNTH), with 95% CIs, when the 95% CI of the RR did not include the null value. We expressed continuous data as mean differences (MDs) with 95% CIs.

    Unit of analysis issues

    If we had identified cluster‐RCTs, we would have included them in the analyses along with individually randomized trials, using the generic inverse variance method. We planned to adjust for the cluster effect using the methods described in the Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews of Interventions, using an estimate of the intracluster correlation coefficient (ICC) derived from the study, or from a similar report, or from a study of a similar population (Higgins 2022). We planned to report this and perform sensitivity analyses to investigate the effect of variation in the ICC (Gluud 2008).

    Dealing with missing data

    We attempted to obtain missing data from study authors. We carried out analyses, as far as possible, on an intention‐to‐treat (ITT) basis (i.e. we attempted to include all participants in the analyses, and analyze all participants in the group to which they were randomized, regardless of whether they received the allocated intervention). The denominator for each outcome in each trial was the number of randomized participants.

    Where the trials did not report means and SDs, and we were unable to obtain these data from the trial authors, we imputed the mean and variance from the median, range, and the size of the sample (Hozo 2005), or we assumed the SD of the outcome was the average of the SDs from all studies that had provided these values. When studies did not report z‐scores, we calculated them using the WHO Child Growth Standards software, adjusting for age and sex (WHO Anthro v3.2.2). We obtained the weighted mean and SD adjusted for the number of participants in each study, based on the methods described in the Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews of Interventions (Higgins 2022).

    We attempted to investigate the impact of imputation on meta‐analyses by way of sensitivity analysis, using the methods suggested in previous publications (Ebrahim 2013; Ebrahim 2014).

    Assessment of heterogeneity

    We evaluated statistical heterogeneity by visually inspecting the forest plots and performing a standard Chi2 test, with a significance level of 0.1. Considering the low power of this test, we also calculated the I2 statistic, which quantifies inconsistency across studies to assess the impact of heterogeneity on meta‐analysis. An I2 statistic of 30% or less indicates a low level of heterogeneity. If we identified moderate heterogeneity (an I2 value of 31% to 49%) or high heterogeneity (an I2 value greater than 75%), we attempted to determine the possible reasons for it by examining individual study characteristics (e.g. participants, interventions, or outcome assessments) and performing subgroup analyses (Higgins 2022).

    Assessment of reporting biases

    If we had included 10 or more studies in a meta‐analysis, we would have explored publication bias by creating funnel plots. We would have tested funnel plot asymmetry with the Egger test for continuous outcomes and the Harbord test for dichotomous outcomes (Egger 1997; Harbord 2006).

    Data synthesis

    We performed meta‐analysis using Review Manager Web (RevMan Web 2022). For dichotomous outcomes (overweight or obesity, all‐cause mortality, adverse events), we calculated the typical estimates of RR and OR, each with its 95% CI. For continuous outcomes (undernutrition, neurodevelopmental outcomes, anthropometric measurements), we calculated the MD with its 95% CI. We used a fixed‐effect model to combine data where it was reasonable to assume that studies were estimating the same underlying treatment effect. If we considered meta‐analysis was inappropriate, we analyzed and interpreted individual trials separately. If there was evidence of clinical heterogeneity, we used a random‐effects model and attempted to explain the heterogeneity based on the different study characteristics and subgroup analyzes (Higgins 2022).

    Subgroup analysis and investigation of heterogeneity

    We conducted subgroup analyses of the primary outcomes for the following factors.

    1. Type of fomula feeding (exclusive or with complementary foods)

    2. Length of treatment (feeding of formula): two months, four months, six months, one year, two years, five years, more than five years

    Sensitivity analysis

    We attempted to perform sensitivity analyses to determine the effect of excluding studies at high or unclear risk of selection bias, performance bias, detection bias, and attrition bias, on the findings for primary outcomes.

    Summary of findings and assessment of the certainty of the evidence

    We used the GRADE approach, as outlined in the GRADE Handbook, to assess the certainty of evidence for the following outcomes (Schünemann 2013).

    1. Underweight

    2. Stunting

    3. Wasting

    4. Overweight

    5. Obesity

    6. All‐cause mortality

    7. Adverse events

    Two review authors (AS and AG) independently assessed the certainty of the evidence for each outcome. We considered evidence from RCTs as high certainty to begin with, downgrading by one level for serious (or two levels for very serious) risk of bias concerns, inconsistency across studies, indirectness of the evidence, imprecision of estimates, or presence of publication bias. We used GRADEpro GDT to create two summary of findings tables to report the certainty of the evidence for the following comparisons.

    1. High‐protein formula versus standard‐protein formula (summary of findings Table 1)

    2. Standard‐protein formula versus low‐protein formula (summary of findings Table 2)

    The GRADE approach assigns one of the following four ratings to a body of evidence.

    1. High certainty: we are very confident that the true effect lies close to that of the estimate of the effect.

    2. Moderate certainty: we are moderately confident in the effect estimate; the true effect is likely to be close to the estimate of the effect, but there is a possibility that it is substantially different.

    3. Low certainty: our confidence in the effect estimate is limited; the true effect may be substantially different from the estimate of the effect.

    4. Very low certainty: we have very little confidence in the effect estimate; the true effect is likely to be substantially different from the estimate of effect.

    Results

    Description of studies

    For detailed information on the trials, see the Characteristics of included studies, Characteristics of excluded studies, Characteristics of studies awaiting classification, and Characteristics of ongoing studies tables.

    Results of the search

    We identified 4459 references from database and trial registry searching and other sources. After removing 1526 duplicates, we screened the titles/abstracts of the remaining 2933 references, excluding 2875 (353 via Screen4Me; see Figure 1). We then retrieved 58 full‐text reports or trial registry records. During full‐text review, we selected 11 studies (14 references) for inclusion, excluded 34 studies (36 references), identified six ongoing studies, and listed two studies as awaiting classification. See Figure 2 for the selection process.

    Included studies

    We included 11 RCTs, which enrolled a total of 1885 infants (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Fomon 1995; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020; Liotto 2018; Picone 1989; Putet 2016; Räihä 1986a; Turck 2006).

    Seven studies (1629 infants) compared high‐protein formula with standard‐protein formula; four of these studies evaluated exclusive formula feeding only (Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Liotto 2018; Turck 2006); two studies evaluated exclusive formula feeding or formula feeding with complementary foods (Koletzko 2009b; Putet 2016); and one study only evaluated formula feeding with complementary foods (Åkeson 1998).

    Four studies (256 infants) compared standard‐protein with low‐protein formula; three of these studies evaluated exclusive formula feeding only (Fomon 1995; Picone 1989; Räihä 1986a); and one evaluated formula as the sole feeding method or in addition to complementary foods (Kouwenhoven 2020).

    For details, see the Characteristics of included studies table.

    Study design

    We obtained data from the published reports of all 11 included RCTs. We also obtained follow‐up data from secondary, observational studies of the participants of six of our included RCTs (Åkeson 1998: Karlsland 1998; Axelsson 1988: Axelsson 1989; Koletzko 2009b: Escribano 2011; Gruszfeld 2016; Totzauer 2022; Weber 2014; Kouwenhoven 2020: Kouwenhoven 2021a; Kouwenhoven 2021b; Picone 1989: Hahn‐Zoric 1990; Räihä 1986a: Räihä 1986b).

    The unit of analysis was the individual participant in all studies. Ten studies included at least one intervention group, a parallel control group, and an observational arm of exclusively breastfed infants. Three of these studies had four arms (Åkeson 1998; Hascoet 2011; Picone 1989), and seven studies had three arms (Axelsson 1988; Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016; Räihä 1986a; Turck 2006). Only Fomon 1995 (a two‐arm trial) did not include an exclusive breastfeeding group.

    Settings

    All studies were conducted in an outpatient setting in high‐income countries (World Bank 2022). Four studies took place in Italy (Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018; Picone 1989; Räihä 1986a); two in Sweden (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988); three in France (Hascoet 2011; Putet 2016; Turck 2006); and one in the USA (Fomon 1995). Studies were conducted from 1980 to 2020. Seven studies were conducted in a single healthcare center (Åkeson 1998; Fomon 1995; Hascoet 2011; Liotto 2018; Picone 1989; Putet 2016; Räihä 1986a); two studies were conducted in multiple centers in the same country (Axelsson 1988; Turck 2006); one study was carried out in multiple centers in five countries (Belgium, Germany, Italy, Poland, and Spain; Koletzko 2009b); and one study was conducted in the Netherlands and Germany (Kouwenhoven 2020).

    Participants

    Baseline characteristics were similar between intervention groups in all included studies; however, we noted the following.

    1. Although all RCTs included term infants, only five specified the participants' gestational age at birth, which ranged from 38.3 weeks to 40.3 weeks (Åkeson 1998; Hascoet 2011; Kouwenhoven 2020; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016); nine studies reported birth weight, which ranged from 3.13 kg to 3.74 kg, and birth height, which ranged from 48.6 cm to 54.6 cm (Åkeson 1998; Fomon 1995; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020; Liotto 2018; Picone 1989; Putet 2016; Räihä 1986a); and three studies reported BMI at baseline, which ranged from 12.7 kg/m2 to 13.9 kg/m2 (Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Turck 2006).

    2. No studies reported the ethnicity of their participants.

    3. In eight studies, male participants constituted 40% to 58% of the sample studied (Åkeson 1998; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020; Liotto 2018; Picone 1989; Putet 2016; Turck 2006); one study included only males (Fomon 1995); and two studies did not report the sex of participants (Axelsson 1988; Räihä 1986a).

    4. Six studies reported their calculation of the study sizes, which ranged from 156 participants to 1679 participants (Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016; Turck 2006).

    5. The main inclusion criteria were singleton pregnancy, gestational age of 37 to 42 weeks, normal weight and height for age at birth, no pregnancy or delivery complications or medical conditions that could limit growth, no physical malformations, and no maternal history of diabetes, chronic diseases, or perinatal infections.

    Interventions and comparisons

    We identified a wide variety of interventions and comparisons, as follows.

    1. In 10 studies, formula feeding was the sole feeding method until the infants were at least four months of age (Axelsson 1988; Fomon 1995; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020; Liotto 2018; Picone 1989; Putet 2016; Räihä 1986a; Turck 2006); in three studies, formula was initially the sole feeding method, and was then given with complementary foods until the infants were at least two years of age (Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020; Putet 2016); and one study only examined formula feeding with complementary foods (Åkeson 1998).

    2. Eight studies reported the proportion of whey and casein in the formulas: they contained from 18% to 70% whey and from 30% to 82% casein (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020; Picone 1989; Putet 2016; Turck 2006).

    3. Regarding the frequency and amount of infant formula feeding, five studies reported that infants consumed at least 125 mL/kg formula per day (Åkeson 1998; Liotto 2018; Picone 1989; Putet 2016; Turck 2006), and three studies only reported that the participants received formula 'ad libitum' (Hascoet 2011; Kouwenhoven 2020; Räihä 1986a).

    4. Six of the 11 studies reported the timing of initiation of infant formula feeding. Two studies started formula feeding on the second day after birth (Fomon 1995; Turck 2006); three studies started in the first month of life (Koletzko 2009b; Picone 1989; Putet 2016), and one study started in the third month (Åkeson 1998). The remaining studies only reported the duration and follow‐up of the intervention.

    Outcomes

    The most common outcome was the measurement of growth by weight, height, head circumference, and BMI over a wide range of time points, from one month to 11 years. Koletzko 2009b and Liotto 2018 also reported their results in z‐scores according to WHO Child Growth Standards (WHO standards 2023).

    Five studies reported adverse events (Hascoet 2011; Kouwenhoven 2020; Liotto 2018; Räihä 1986a; Turck 2006); two studies reported serum glucose levels and insulin secretion (Axelsson 1988; Putet 2016); one study reported serum albumin and urea levels (Fomon 1995); one study reported gut microbiota (Hascoet 2011), and one study reported protein metabolism (Picone 1989).

    Funding sources

    All studies received funding from at least one commercial company: Nestlé funded five studies (Åkeson 1998; Hascoet 2011; Putet 2016; Räihä 1986a; Turck 2006); Danone S.A. funded two studies (Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020); Ross Laboratories funded two studies (Åkeson 1998; Picone 1989); Findus funded one study (Axelsson 1988), and Humana Italia SpA funded one study (Liotto 2018).

    Two studies received partial funding from the Bristol‐Myers Squibb Company (Fomon 1995; Koletzko 2009b). Five studies received funding from multiple sources such as governments, foundations, or commercial companies (Åkeson 1998; Fomon 1995; Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020).

    Conflicts of interest

    Three studies clearly detailed the activities of their sponsors (Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020; Liotto 2018); sponsor involvement was unclear in five studies (Axelsson 1988; Fomon 1995; Picone 1989; Räihä 1986a; Turck 2006); and sponsors appeared to be involved in critical procedures in three studies (Åkeson 1998; Hascoet 2011; Putet 2016). For more details, see the Characteristics of included studies table.

    Excluded studies

    We excluded 34 studies for the following reasons.

    1. Ineligible intervention (12 studies: ACTRN12614000918628; ACTRN12620000552987; Inostroza 2014; Kuehn 2022; Lönnerdal 1998; Lowe 1964; Martin 2014; NCT02469402; Taitz 1989; Timby 2014; Trabulsi 2011; Ziegler 2015)

    2. Ineligible comparator (10 studies: Axelsson 1987; Chen 2010; Harrison 1987; Heinig 1993; Jinno 2020; Jury 1991; Lönnerdal 1990; NCT02010749; NTR1199; Rähiä 2002)

    3. Formula feeding lacking details of protein content (six studies: NCT00465764; NCT00916565; NCT00977964; NCT01489098; NCT02481531; NCT02658500)

    4. Protocol discontinued due to insufficient participant recruitment (two studies: NCT02433600; NCT04859231)

    5. Study design inappropriate for this review (two studies: Haschke‐Becher 2016; Lifschitz 2016)

    6. Study retraction by the author (Tseng 1990)

    7. Formula feeding period less than three months (Gunn 1986)

    For more details, see the Characteristics of excluded studies table.

    Ongoing studies

    We identified the following six ongoing studies.

    1. NCT01300000: an RCT that began in 2011, to evaluate the effect on weight gain and gastrointestinal tolerability of a calorie‐ and protein‐reduced formula versus a standard formula, administered for one year

    2. NCT02282488: an RCT that began in 2006, to evaluate the effect on body composition of a high‐protein formula versus a low‐protein formula, administered for one year

    3. NCT02646969: an RCT that began in 2016, to analyze the effect on weight gain of regimen 1 versus regimen 2 formula, administered for one year

    4. NCT02907502: an RCT that began in 2016 to analyze the effect on development of overweight and obesity of a high‐protein formula versus a low‐protein formula, administered for one year

    5. NCT03456934: an RCT that began in 2017 to evaluate the effect on weight gain and adverse events of a standard‐protein versus a low‐protein formula, administered for one year

    6. NCT03513991: an RCT that began in 2016 to analyze the effect on weight and adverse events at one year of two standard protein formulas versus a low protein formula

    For further information, see the Characteristics of ongoing studies table.

    Studies awaiting classification

    The following two studies, available only as conference abstracts, are awaiting classification.

    1. Beck 2009: an oral presentation at the 50th Annual Meeting of the European Society for Pediatric Research

    2. Shingal 2010: an abstract presented in 2010

    For details, see the Characteristics of studies awaiting classification table.

    Allocation

    Random sequence generation

    Fomon 1995 reported having allocated participants alternatively; we judged the study at high risk of bias as this is an inadequate randomization method that does not avoid selection bias. Two studies provided insufficient information on how the infants were randomly assigned to permit a judgment, so we considered them at unclear risk of bias (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988).

    Allocation concealment

    We considered three trials at low risk of bias because the reported allocation concealment techniques involved sequentially numbered and sealed envelopes, internet‐based randomization platform, or code‐numbered labels without identification of protein content (Axelsson 1988; Koletzko 2009b; Putet 2016). The remaining eight trials did not report allocation concealment in detail (unclear risk of bias).

    Blinding

    Blinding of participants and personnel

    Only Axelsson 1988 did not report how the blinding was performed (unclear risk of bias). The remaining 10 studies adequately reported how blinding was performed or mentioned that their formulas were almost identical in composition, making them indistinguishable from each other. We judged these 10 studies at low risk of performance bias.

    Blinding of outcome assessment

    Six studies provided sufficient information on the blinding of outcome assessment so were at low risk of detection bias (Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Kouwenhoven 2020; Liotto 2018; Räihä 1986a). The remaining five studies provided insufficient detail to determine whether blinding of outcome assessment was suitable (unclear risk of bias).

    Incomplete outcome data

    We judged eight of the 11 studies at low risk of attrition bias because their attrition rates were below 20%. Attrition rates in the remaining three studies ranged from 25% to 44% due to the difficulty of conducting long‐term follow‐up; we considered them at high risk of bias (Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Turck 2006).

    Selective reporting

    We judged all 11 studies at low risk of reporting bias because, despite the lack of published protocols or trial registries, they reported all specified outcomes. Given that eight of 11 studies (73%) were published before 2010, we did not expect them to have a preregistered protocol (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Fomon 1995; Koletzko 2009b; Picone 1989; Putet 2016; Räihä 1986a; Turck 2006).

    Other potential sources of bias

    We judged three studies at high risk of other bias, mainly because the sponsor was involved in the analysis of the results or because at least one study author was employed by the sponsor (Åkeson 1998; Hascoet 2011; Putet 2016). We judged five studies at unclear risk of other bias because the information provided was insufficient to determine the involvement of the sponsor (Axelsson 1988; Fomon 1995; Picone 1989; Räihä 1986a; Turck 2006).

    Effects of interventions

    See: Summary of findings 1 High‐protein formula versus standard‐protein formula in healthy term infants; Summary of findings 2 Standard‐protein formula versus low‐protein formula in healthy term infants

    Because nine studies did not report z‐scores for the weight, height, head circumference, or BMI of their participants, we used the reported anthropometric measures to calculate weighted mean z‐score values using the WHO Child Growth Standards software, adjusting for age, sex, and the number of participants in each study (WHO Anthro v3.2.2).

    High‐protein formula versus standard‐protein formula

    See summary of findings Table 1.

    Seven studies (including 1629 participants) compared infants who were fed high‐protein formula with those fed standard‐protein formula (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016; Turck 2006). In six studies, the infants were fed only formula for four months (Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016; Turck 2006), and then in two of those studies, the infants were kept on formula (with the same protein content) after moving on to complementary foods, for at least one year of follow‐up (Koletzko 2009b; Putet 2016). In Åkeson 1998, the infants received formula in addition to complementary foods throughout the study.

    Primary outcomes
    1. Undernutrition

    We were unable to calculate the RR or Peto OR for the different types of undernutrition because no studies provided dichotomous data for these outcomes (number of participants with the outcome); however, since all the studies provided continuous data, we calculated the z‐scores for each study and used the MD as the pooled effect measure.

    a) Underweight (weight‐for‐age z‐score)

    Two studies provided weight‐for‐age z‐scores (Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018), and five studies provided data that we could use to calculate weight‐for‐age z‐scores (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Putet 2016; Turck 2006). We are unsure if feeding healthy term infants high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula has any effect on weight‐for‐age z‐score in the first year of life (MD 0.05 SDs, 95% CI −0.09 to 0.19; P = 0.51, I2 = 61%; 7 studies, 1629 participants; very low‐certainty evidence; Analysis 1.1).

    We performed a subgroup analysis according to type of formula feeding (exclusive/with complementary foods). Among the exclusively formula‐fed infants, there was no difference in weight‐for‐age z‐score between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula at four months of follow‐up (MD −0.10 SDs, 95% CI −0.24 to 0.04; P = 0.16, I2 = 3%; 4 studies, 311 participants; Analysis 1.1). Among the infants given formula in addition to complementary foods, there was a difference in weight‐for‐age z‐score between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula at one year of follow‐up (MD 0.20 SDs, 95% CI 0.11 to 0.30; P < 0.001, I2 = 0%; 3 studies, 1318 participants; Analysis 1.1). The P value of the test for subgroup differences was less than 0.001.

    Three of the seven studies were at high risk of attrition bias (Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Turck 2006). When we removed these studies in an overall sensitivity analysis, the effect estimate did not change (MD 0.0 SDs, 95% CI −0.27 to 0.26; P = 0.98, I2 = 72%; 4 studies, 361 participants). In a detailed sensitivity analysis by type of formula feeding, we found a slight change in the effect estimate between the high‐protein and standard‐protein groups among exclusively formula‐fed infants (MD −0.28 SDs, 95% CI −0.53 to −0.03; P = 0.03, I2 = 0%; 2 studies, 133 participants) and among infants fed formula with complementary foods (MD 0.21 SDs, 95% CI 0.05 to 0.37; P = 0.009, I2 = 0%; 2 studies, 228 participants).

    In a subgroup analysis according to different follow‐up time points, we identified that the weight‐for‐age z‐score of participants in the high‐protein group relative to the standard‐protein group gradually increased from an MD of −0.01 SDs (95% CI −0.13 to 0.10; P = 0.80, I2 = 43%; 4 studies, 1458 participants; Analysis 1.2) at two months to an MD of 0.15 SDs (95% CI 0.01 to 0.29; P = 0.03; 1 study, 1090 participants; Analysis 1.2) at six years of follow‐up. The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.01.

    To determine whether the change in weight‐for‐age over time was affected by the high‐protein formula, we performed meta‐regression and linear regression with panel‐corrected standard error analyses adjusted for study weight in STATA v15.1 software (Stata 2017). The results suggested no effect (P = 0.16 for meta‐regression, and P = 0.38 for linear regression).

    b) Stunting (height‐for‐age z‐score)

    Two studies provided height‐for‐age z‐scores (Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018), and five studies provided data that we could use to calculate height‐for‐age z‐scores (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Putet 2016; Turck 2006). We are unsure if feeding healthy term infants high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula has any effect on height‐for‐age z‐score in the first year of life (MD 0.15 SDs, 95% CI −0.05 to 0.35; P = 0.14, I2 = 73%; 7 studies, 1629 participants; very low‐certainty evidence; Analysis 1.3).

    We performed a subgroup analysis according to type of formula feeding (exclusive/with complementary foods). Among the exclusively formula‐fed infants, there was no difference in height‐for‐age z‐score between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula at four months of follow‐up (MD 0.01 SDs, 95% CI −0.32 to 0.34; P = 0.97, I2 = 73%; 4 studies, 311 participants; Analysis 1.3). Among the infants given formula in addition to complementary foods, those fed high‐protein formula had a higher height‐for‐age z‐score compared with those fed standard‐protein formula at one year of follow‐up (MD 0.29 SDs, 95% CI 0.02 to 0.57; P = 0.04, I2 = 78%; 3 studies, 1318 participants; Analysis 1.3). The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.19.

    Three of the seven studies were at high risk of attrition bias (Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Turck 2006). When we removed these studies in an overall sensitivity analysis, the effect estimate did not change (MD 0.18 SDs, 95% CI −0.19 to 0.55; P = 0.35, I2 = 81%; 4 studies, 361 participants). In a detailed sensitivity analysis by type of formula feeding, we found a slight change in the effect estimate between the high‐protein and standard‐protein groups among exclusively formula‐fed infants (MD −0.11 SDs, 95% CI −0.67 to 0.45; P = 0.69, I2 = 76%; 2 studies, 133 participants) and among infants fed formula with complementary foods (MD 0.43 SDs, 95% CI 0.25 to 0.62; P < 0.001, I2 = 0%; 2 studies, 228 participants).

    In a subgroup analysis according to different follow‐up time points, we identified that the height‐for‐age z‐score of participants in the high‐protein group relative to the standard‐protein group gradually increased, from an MD of −0.00 SDs (95% CI −0.17 to 0.17; P = 1.0, I2 = 49%; 4 studies, 1458 participants; Analysis 1.4) at two months to an MD of 0.29 SDs (95% CI 0.02 to 0.57; P = 0.04, I2 = 78%; 3 studies, 1318 participants; Analysis 1.4) at one year of follow‐up; but this increase in height‐for‐age z‐score was no longer observed at two years (MD −0.07 SDs, 95% CI −0.17 to 0.03; P = 0.17; 1 study, 1090 participants; Analysis 1.4), or six years (MD −0.04 SDs, 95% CI −0.17 to 0.09; P = 0.54; 1 study, 1090 participants; Analysis 1.4). The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.13.

    Meta‐regression analysis and linear regression with panel‐corrected standard error analyses showed that the change in height‐for‐age over time was not influenced by the type of infant formula (P = 0.94 for meta‐regression and P = 0.86 for linear regression).

    c) Wasting (weight‐for‐height z‐score)

    Two studies provided weight‐for‐height z‐scores (Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018), and five studies provided data that we could use to calculate weight‐for‐height z‐scores (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Putet 2016; Turck 2006). We are unsure if feeding healthy term infants high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula has any effect on weight‐for‐height z‐score in the first year of life (MD −0.12 SDs, 95% CI −0.31 to 0.07; P = 0.20, I2 = 94%; 7 studies, 1629 participants; very low‐certainty evidence; Analysis 1.5).

    We performed a subgroup analysis according to type of formula feeding (exclusive/with complementary foods). Among the exclusively formula‐fed infants, there was no difference in weight‐for‐height z‐score between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula at four months of follow‐up (MD −0.20 SDs, 95% CI −0.41 to 0.01; P = 0.07, I2 = 93%; 4 studies, 311 participants; Analysis 1.5). Among the infants given formula in addition to complementary foods, there was also no difference in weight‐for‐height z‐score between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula at one year of follow‐up (MD −0.02 SDs, 95% CI −0.37 to 0.32; P = 0.90, I2 = 93%; 3 studies, 1318 participants; Analysis 1.5).     Three of the seven studies were at high risk of attrition bias (Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Turck 2006). The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.10.

    2. Overweight or obesity

    One study reported the risk of developing overweight or obesity in infants fed formula in addition to complementary foods (Koletzko 2009b).

    a. Overweight

    We are unsure if feeding healthy term infants high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula has any effect on the risk of overweight in the first five years of life (RR 1.26, 95% CI 0.63 to 2.51; P = 0.51; 1 study, 1090 participants; very low‐certainty evidence; Analysis 1.7).

    In an analysis of different time points of follow‐up, we found that the risk of developing overweight in participants in the high‐protein group relative to the standard‐protein group ranged from an RR of 1.26 (95% CI 0.63 to 2.51; P = 0.51; 1 study, 1090 participants; Analysis 1.8) at five years to an RR of 1.16 (95% CI 0.83 to 1.64; P = 0.39; 1 study, 1090 participants; Analysis 1.8) at 11 years of follow‐up. The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.90.

    We could not perform sensitivity analysis because only one study reported this outcome.

    b. Obesity

    We are unsure if feeding healthy term infants high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula has any effect on the risk of obesity in the first five years of life (RR 1.96, 95% CI 0.59 to 6.48; P = 0.27; 1 study, 1090 participants; very low‐certainty evidence; Analysis 1.9).

    In a subgroup analysis according to different follow‐up time points, we observed that the risk of developing obesity in participants in the high‐protein group relative to the standard‐protein group ranged from an RR of 1.96 (95% CI 0.59 to 6.48; P = 0.27; 1 study, 1090 participants; Analysis 1.10) at five years to an RR of 1.28 (95% CI 0.63 to 2.62; P = 0.49; 1 study, 1090 participants; Analysis 1.10) at 11 years of follow‐up. The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.65.

    We could not perform sensitivity analysis because only one study reported this outcome.

    Secondary outcomes
    1. Neurodevelopmental outcomes

    One observational study of the participants in Koletzko 2009b reported neurodevelopment outcomes up to eight years of age, using the following instruments (Escribano 2016).

    1. Memory using the recall objects test and the Rey auditory verbal learning test (Rey 1941; Snodgrass 1980)

    2. Attention using the continuous performance test and the cancelation test (Tachar) of Woodcook‐Muñoz (Conners 2003; Sousa‐Magalhães 2012)

    3. Perception using the Hooper visual organization test (Maria 2012)

    4. Language with Animals – FAS (measure of phonemic word fluency that asks the individual to orally produce as many words as possible that begin with the letters F, A, and S within 1 minute; Patterson 2011) and Nepsy's token test (NEPSY‐II; Vought 2011)

    5. Processing speed using the symbol digit modalities test (Hooper 1983)

    6. Motor by grooved pegboard test (Lopez 2003)

    7. Executive functions using the Stroop (first to fourth condition), reversal digits (of Woodcook–Muñoz battery of tests), Kaufman‐ABC II pattern reasoning, children's color trail test, and hungry donkey task (Smith 2007; Vought 2011)

    8. Behavior using the child behavior checklist 4 to 18 (CBCL; Achenbach 1991)

    Overall, Escribano 2016 reported no differences in any of the behavioral or performance domains between participants in the two feeding groups.

    2. All‐cause mortality

    No studies reported all‐cause mortality.

    3. Adverse events

    Four studies (involving 445 participants) reported adverse events (Hascoet 2011; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016; Turck 2006). Of these studies, only Putet 2016 administered infant formula in addition to complementary foods. The most common adverse events were diarrhea, vomiting, and milk hypersensitivity. In total, 70 of the 226 infants (31%) who received high‐protein formula experienced at least one adverse event, compared with 75 of the 219 infants (34%) who received standard‐protein formula. The evidence suggests there may be little or no difference in the occurrence of adverse events between infants fed high‐protein formula and infants fed standard‐protein formula in the first year of life (RR 0.93, 95% CI 0.76 to 1.13; P = 0.44, I2 = 0%; 4 studies, 445 participants; low‐certainty evidence; Analysis 1.11).

    We performed a subgroup analysis according to type of formula feeding (exclusive/with complementary foods). Among the exclusively formula‐fed infants, there was no difference in risk of adverse event between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula at four months of follow‐up (RR 0.95, 95% CI 0.78 to 1.16; P = 0.63, I2 = 0%; 3 studies, 291 participants; Analysis 1.11). Among the infants given formula in addition to complementary foods, there was also no difference in risk of adverse events between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula at one year of follow‐up (RR 0.19, 95% CI 0.01 to 3.79; P = 0.27; 1 study, 154 participants; Analysis 1.11). The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.29.

    Two of the four studies were at high risk of attrition bias (Hascoet 2011; Turck 2006). When we removed these studies in an overall sensitivity analysis, the effect estimate did not change (RR 0.82, 95% CI 0.55 to 1.22; P = 0.32, I2 = 5%; 2 studies, 267 participants). In a detailed sensitivity analysis by type of formula feeding, we found that the effect estimate did not change among the infants who were exclusively formula‐fed (RR 0.88, 95% CI 0.59 to 1.31; P = 0.52; 1 study, 113 participants) or among infants fed formula with complementary foods (RR 0.19, 95% CI 0.01 to 3.79; P = 0.27; 1 study, 154 participants).

    We performed a detailed analysis by type of adverse event. In the infants fed only formula, we found no difference between the high‐protein group and the standard‐protein group in the risk of vomiting (Peto OR 3.29, 95% CI 0.55 to 19.61; P = 0.19; 1 study, 113 participants; Analysis 1.12) or milk hypersensitivity (Peto OR 2.91, 95% CI 0.39 to 21.51; P = 0.30; 1 study, 77 participants; Analysis 1.12). In the infants given formula in addition to complementary foods, we found no difference between the high‐protein group and the standard‐protein group in the risk of diarrhea (Peto OR 0.12, 95% CI 0.01 to 1.99; P = 0.14; 1 study, 154 participants; Analysis 1.13) or vomiting (Peto OR 0.12, 95% CI 0.0 to 6.31; P = 0.30; 1 study, 154 participants; Analysis 1.13).

    No studies reported the risk of developing renal insufficiency.

    4. Anthropometric measurements

    Seven studies reported anthropometric measurements (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016; Turck 2006).

    a) Weight

    Seven studies reported weight (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016; Turck 2006). There was no difference in weight between infants fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula in the first year of life (MD −0.01 kg, 95% CI −0.12 to 0.09; P = 0.83, I2 = 55%; 7 studies, 1629 participants; Analysis 1.14) in the first year of life.

    We performed a subgroup analysis according to type of formula feeding (exclusive/with complementary foods). Among the exclusively formula‐fed infants, there was no difference in weight between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula at four months of follow‐up (MD −0.07 kg, 95% CI −0.18 to 0.04; P = 0.24, I2 = 35%; 4 studies, 311 participants; Analysis 1.14). Among the infants given formula in addition to complementary foods, there was also no difference in weight between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula at one year of follow‐up (MD 0.09 kg, 95% CI −0.12 to 0.29; P = 0.42, I2 = 64%; 3 studies, 1318 participants; Analysis 1.14). The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.21.

    Three of the seven studies were at high risk of attrition bias (Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Turck 2006). When we removed these studies in an overall sensitivity analysis, the effect estimate did not change (MD −0.10 kg, 95% CI −0.24 to 0.05; P = 0.21, I2 = 38%; 4 studies, 361 participants). In a detailed sensitivity analysis by type of formula feeding, we found a slight change in the effect estimate between the high‐protein and standard‐protein groups among exclusively formula‐fed infants (MD −0.19 kg, 95% CI −0.33 to −0.04; P = 0.01, I2 = 0%; 2 studies, 133 participants) and among infants fed formula with complementary foods (MD 0.03 kg, 95% CI −0.28 to 0.34; P = 0.85, I2 = 63%; 2 studies, 228 participants).

    In a subgroup analysis according to different follow‐up time points, we observed a gradual increase in weight in infants fed the high‐protein formula compared with the standard‐protein group, from an MD of −0.03 kg (95% CI −0.09 to 0.04; P = 0.40, I2 = 11%; 4 studies, 1458 participants; Analysis 1.15) at two months to an MD of 0.61 kg (95% CI 0.12 to 1.10; P = 0.01; 1 study, 1090 participants; Analysis 1.15) at six years of follow‐up. The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.001.

    b) Height

    Seven studies reported height (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016; Turck 2006). There was no difference in height between infants fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula in the first year of life (MD 0.27 cm, 95% CI −0.19 to 0.74; P = 0.25, I2 = 77%; 7 studies, 1629 participants; Analysis 1.16).

    We performed a subgroup analysis according to type of formula feeding (exclusive/with complementary foods). Among the exclusively formula‐fed infants, there was no difference in height between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula among the exclusively formula‐fed infants (MD 0.16 cm, 95% CI −0.39 to 0.72; P = 0.56, I2 = 71%; 4 studies, 311 participants; Analysis 1.16). Among the infants given formula in addition to complementary foods, there was no difference in height between those fed high‐protein formula and those fed standard‐protein formula at one year of follow‐up (MD 0.49 cm, 95% CI −0.52 to 1.50; P = 0.34, I2 = 87%; 3 studies, 1318 participants; Analysis 1.16). The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.58.

    Three of the seven studies were at high risk of attrition bias (Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Turck 2006). When we removed these studies in an overall sensitivity analysis, the effect estimate did not change (MD 0.44 cm, 95% CI −0.21 to 1.10; P = 0.19, I2 = 68%; 4 studies, 361 participants). In a detailed sensitivity analysis by subgroups, we found that the effect estimate changed among the infants who received formula in addition to complementary foods (MD 1.00 cm, 95% CI 0.45 to 1.54; P = 0.004, I2 = 0%; 2 studies, 228 participants), but not among the infants who were fed only formula (MD −0.04 cm, 95% CI −1.00 to 0.91; P = 0.93, I2 = 71%; 2 studies, 133 participants).

    In a subgroup analysis according to different follow‐up time points, we observed a gradual increase in height in infants fed the high‐protein formula compared with those in the standard‐protein group, from an MD of 0.04 cm (95% CI −0.33 to 0.42; P = 0.82, I2 = 44%; 4 studies, 1458 participants; Analysis 1.17) at two months to an MD of 1.00 cm (95% CI 0.45 to 1.54; P < 0.01, I2 = 0%; 2 studies, 228 participants; Analysis 1.17) at one year of follow‐up. However, the MD at two years was −0.30 cm (95% CI −0.67 to 0.07; P = 0.12; 1 study, 1090 participants; Analysis 1.17), and the MD at six years was −0.10 cm (95% CI −0.76 to 0.56; P = 0.77; 1 study, 1090 participants; Analysis 1.17). The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.01.

    C) Body mass index

    Seven studies reported BMI z‐score or provided data that we could use to calculate BMI z‐score (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016; Turck 2006). The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.02.

    Seven studies reported BMI in kg/m2 (Åkeson 1998; Axelsson 1988; Hascoet 2011; Koletzko 2009b; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016; Turck 2006). The meta‐analysis showed no difference in BMI between infants fed high‐protein formula compared with the standard‐protein group in the first year of life (MD −0.22 kg/m2, 95% CI −0.53 to 0.09; P = 0.17, I2 = 95%, 7 studies, 1629 participants; Analysis 1.20).

    We performed a subgroup analysis according to type of formula feeding (exclusive/with complementary foods). Among the exclusively formula‐fed infants, BMI was lower in those fed high‐protein formula compared with those fed standard‐protein formula at four months of follow‐up (MD −0.32 kg/m2, 95% CI −0.59 to −0.04; P = 0.03, I2 = 91%; 4 studies, 311 participants; Analysis 1.20).     D) Head circumference

    Three studies reported head circumference z‐score or provided data that we could use to calculate head circumference z‐score (Hascoet 2011; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016).     In a subgroup analysis according to different follow‐up time points, we observed a gradual increase in head circumference z‐score in infants fed high‐protein formula compared with the standard‐protein group, from an MD of 0.25 SDs (95% CI −0.18 to 0.68; P = 0.25, I2 = 70%; 2 studies, 267 participants; Analysis 1.23) at two months to an MD of 0.56 SDs (95% CI 0.34 to 0.78; P < 0.01 ; 1 study, 154 participants; Analysis 1.23) at five years of follow‐up. The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.49.

    Three studies reported head circumference in cm (Hascoet 2011; Liotto 2018; Putet 2016). The meta‐analysis showed no difference in head circumference between infants fed high‐protein formula and infants fed standard‐protein formula in the first year of life (MD 0.32 cm, 95% CI 0.0 to 0.63; P = 0.05, I2 = 0%; 3 studies, 344 participants; Analysis 1.24).

    One of the three studies was at high risk of attrition bias (Hascoet 2011). In a detailed sensitivity analysis by subgroups, we found an MD of 0.20 cm (95% CI −0.37 to 0.77; P = 0.49; 1 study, 113 participants) among the infants who were fed only formula. We were unable to calculate the effect estimate for infants given formula in addition to complementary foods.

    In a subgroup analysis according to different follow‐up time points, we observed a gradual increase in head circumference in infants fed the high‐protein formula compared with the standard‐protein group, from an MD of 0.24 cm (95% CI −0.35 to 0.82; P = 0.43, I2 = 67%; 2 studies, 267 participants; Analysis 1.25) at two months to an MD of 0.80 cm (95% CI 0.37 to 1.23; P < 0.01; 1 study, 154 participants; Analysis 1.25) at five years of follow‐up. The P value of the test for subgroup differences was 0.56.

    Standard‐protein formula versus low‐protein formula

    See summary of findings Table 2.

    Four studies (involving 256 participants) evaluated infants who were fed standard‐protein formula versus infants fed low‐protein formula (Fomon 1995; Kouwenhoven 2020; Picone 1989; Räihä 1986a). In all studies, infants received formula as the sole feeding method for four months. The participants of Kouwenhoven 2020 also received infant formula with complementary foods up to two years of age (reported in Kouwenhoven 2021b, an observational study).

    3. Adverse events

    Two studies (involving 206 participants) reported adverse events (Fomon 1995; Kouwenhoven 2020). The most common events were diarrhea, vomiting, and milk hypersensitivity. In both studies, the children were exclusively formula‐fed for the first four months of life.

    In total, 17 of the 101 participants (17%) who received standard‐protein formula experienced at least one adverse event, compared with 12 of the 105 infants (11%) who received low‐protein formula. There may be little or no difference in adverse events between healthy term infants fed standard‐protein formula and those fed low‐protein formula in the first four months of life (Peto OR 1.55, 95% CI 0.70 to 3.40; P = 0.28, I2 = 0%; 2 studies, 206 participants; low‐certainty evidence; Analysis 2.7).

    One of the four studies was at high risk of selection bias (Fomon 1995). When we removed it in an overall sensitivity analysis, the effect estimate did not change (Peto OR 1.44, 95% CI 0.64 to 3.22; P = 0.38; 1 study, 178 participants).

    We performed a detailed analysis by type of adverse event. We found no difference between the standard‐protein group and the low‐protein group in the risk of diarrhea (Peto OR 1.44, 95% CI 0.64 to 3.22; P = 0.38; 1 study, 178 participants; Analysis 2.8), vomiting (Peto OR 0.44, 95% CI 0.12 to 1.57; P = 0.21; 1 study, 178 participants; Analysis 2.8), or milk hypersensitivity (Peto OR 0.63, 95% CI 0.24 to 1.67; P = 0.36, I2 = 0.44%; 2 studies, 206 participants; Analysis 2.8) during the first four months of life.
