    Assessment of reporting bias

    As no meta‐analysis included 10 studies or more, we did not create any funnel plots.

    Discussion

    Summary of main results

    This review included 11 parallel‐group RCTs with individual randomization; 10 studies included an observational group of exclusively breastfed infants. For six of the 11 trials, we found secondary observational studies with follow‐up information. We extracted data from these observational studies to complete the analyses.

    The studies analyzed 1885 healthy term infants with weight and height within 2 SDs of the WHO Child Growth Standards' median (WHO standards 2023). All the studies were set in high‐income countries. The infants were fed from day two of life to two years of age with formulas of varying amounts of protein, ranging from 1.2 g to 2.9 g/100 kcal. In some studies, participants were followed‐up beyond two years (up to 11 years of age in one study).

    Of all the participants in the completed studies, 809 were assigned to high‐protein formula (≥ 2.5 g protein/100 kcal), 951 infants were assigned to standard‐protein formula (1.8 g to < 2.5 g protein/100 kcal), and 125 were assigned to low‐protein formula (< 1.8 g protein/100 kcal); 954 control infants were exclusively breastfed. The trials assessed anthropometric parameters (weight, height, BMI, head circumference), protein metabolism (albumin, urea serum levels), gut microbiota, and adverse events.

    In view of the considerable variation among the interventions, in terms of the protein content of the formulas, the type of formula feeding (exclusive or with complementary foods), and the follow‐up time, we divided the comparisons into two groups to analyze the efficacy and safety of infant formula feeding with the least possible heterogeneity.

    Overall, in this review's main comparison, the findings suggest that high‐protein formula compared with standard‐protein formula may have no little or no effect on undernutrition, overweight, or obesity; however, the certainty of the evidence is very low. Although we observed that high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula led to an increase in weight‐for‐age z‐score (0.20 SDs) and height‐for age z‐score (0.29 SDs) when given with complementary foods in infants from four months of age, this appears to reflect overall growth.

    The meta‐analysis suggested that there may be no increased risk of adverse events (e.g. diarrhea, vomiting, milk hypersensitivity) with high‐protein formula compared to standard‐protein formula among infants who were fed only formula and among infants who were fed formula in addition to complementary foods.

    The findings for our second comparison suggest that standard‐protein formula compared to low‐protein formula may have little or no effect on undernutrition, overweight, or obesity; however, the certainty of the evidence is very low. Among infants who were fed formula in addition to complementary foods, we found an increase in height‐for age (0.8 cm), but this also appears to reflect overall growth.

    The meta‐analysis suggested that there may be no increased risk of adverse events with standard‐protein formula compared to low‐protein formula among infants who are exclusively formula‐fed fed during the first four months of life.

    There was insufficient data to analyze all‐cause mortality, renal insufficiency, or neurological development in infants. The results of this review may change if and when we incorporate data from the six ongoing trials and the two trials pending classification in future updates.

    Overall completeness and applicability of evidence

    Although this review included seven trials (1629 infants) with the main comparison of high‐protein formula versus standard‐protein formula, their effects on infant nutrition remain uncertain. This is because the available data on weight and height were limited and heterogeneous, both in infants fed only formula and in infants fed formula with complementary foods, impacting the certainty of the evidence.

    Although all the studies evaluated the growth of formula‐fed infants, only two trials reported z‐scores. Consequently, for the remaining trials, we had to use the reported data and calculate weighted mean z‐score values using the WHO Child Growth Standards software (WHO Anthro v3.2.2), adjusting for age, sex, and number of participants in each study, to obtain a standard measure and perform the analyses of the different outcomes. Therefore, it is important that future studies standardize the reporting of participants' growth measures, and include data on all‐cause mortality, renal insufficiency, and neurodevelopment. The addition of these data could improve the certainty of the results.

    Quality of the evidence

    The formulas comprised a variety of whey/casein ratios in the intervention and comparison groups. In addition, the timing of participant initiation and follow‐up varied among the groups, and there were differences in whether infants were exclusively formula‐fed or given formula with complementary foods. Furthermore, although all trials analyzed participants' growth, the results were reported in different ways, increasing heterogeneity between the trials.

    Although allocation concealment was unclear in most trials, and we considered three trials at high risk of attrition bias (because attrition rates exceeded 20%), we observed no reporting bias. The certainty of the evidence was generally low or very low, mainly owing to risk of bias and imprecision (low number of trials, and wide CIs consistent with benefit and harm).

    Potential biases in the review process

    We followed standard Cochrane methodology and applied no restrictions on language or date of publication when searching for studies. We added information from observational studies to complete the follow‐up of participants. Two of four review authors independently selected studies, extracted data, and assessed risk of bias and certainty of the evidence; a fifth review author resolved discrepancies to minimize review bias. When we identified substantial heterogeneity in the analyses, we explored possible causes by stratifying the data.

    Because almost half of the trials were conducted before the 2000s and the reporting of the information varied widely, we had to standardize data using the WHO Child Growth Standards (WHO standards 2023).

    Agreements and disagreements with other studies or reviews

    The results of this review are consistent with those reported in one of the included trials (Koletzko 2009b), and in one systematic review published in 2020 (Fenton 2020), though there are key differences.

    • Koletzko 2009b, a multicenter trial involving 1138 infants, reported that high‐protein formula was associated with increased weight, weight‐for‐length, and BMI from six months of age. Therefore, the study authors reasoned that feeding infants formula containing 1.8 g protein/100 kcal could reduce the later risk of overweight and obesity. However, the trial's high risk of attrition bias could have affected the findings in terms of height gain.

    • Fenton 2020 found that in low birth weight infants who were exclusively formula‐fed, those fed 3.0 to 4.0 g of protein/kg/day compared with those fed low‐protein formula gained more weight (MD 2.36 g/kg/day, 95% CI 1.31 to 3.40; 5 studies, 114 participants) and height (MD 0.16 cm/week, 95% CI 0.02 to 0.34; 2 studies, 48 participants); however, the infants in Fenton 2020 had different characteristics and different energy requirements compared to the infants in our review.

    Our findings are inconsistent with those reported in two other systematic reviews (Druet 2012; Patro‐Gołąb 2016).

    • Patro‐Gołąb 2016 observed that healthy infants younger than three years who were fed high‐protein formula grew more in length than those fed low‐protein formula in the first three months of life (MD 0.27 cm, 95% CI 0.02 to 0.52; P = 0.03; I2 = 42%; 4 RCTs, 998 participants). However, this difference disappeared when the participants reached one year of age, possibly because Patro‐Gołąb 2016 did not analyze the growth of the participants in terms of z‐score values (the usual method of assessment; CDC 2009).

    • Druet 2012 is a systematic review of observational studies with 4766 participants. It concluded that infants fed with high‐protein formulas during the first 12 years of life had an increased risk of developing obesity (OR 1.97, 95% CI 1.83 to 2.12; P = 0.21; I2 = 30%; 10 cohorts, 47661 participants). However, the design of the studies included in the review limit the certainty of the evidence.
